;; ch16-whats-next.book.slatl
;; Book of CS Curriculum — Chapter 16 — advanced1 tier (closing)
;; Authored 2026-07-16.
;; Scoured 2026-07-17 (Jess): removed corporate-model attribution banner,
;; dialect narrowed to motoi, voice de-personified.

(dialect :applies ("motoi") :note "Motoi Scheme.")

(chapter
  :book             "Book of CS Curriculum"
  :chapter-number   16
  :title            "What's Next"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :audience         "kid"
  :tier             :advanced1
  :author-lane      "chapter-lane-B-2026-07-16"
  :provenance       ((:authored-by "chapter-lane-B-2026-07-16"))
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality  "public"
  :voice            "teaching"
  :prose
"(chapter
  :n 16
  :title \"What's next\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You finished the book. That is not a small thing. You read fifteen
   chapters that most adults who work in this field have never sat down
   with in one place. You have opinions now — about lists versus arrays,
   about when hash tables lie, about why networks fail, about what a bit
   really is. Opinions are the thing you leave a book with. They are
   what will guide the next thing you build.

   This chapter is a map of the rest of the country. You have walked one
   trail through the forest. Here are the other trails, so you can pick
   one and go.\"

  :the-shape-of-the-field
  \"Computer science is roughly six large countries, each with its own
   dialect and its own kind of problem. You have visited all of them a
   little. Now, brief tours of each, so you can pick which one to live
   in for a while.

   Algorithms and data structures — the country you know best now. The
   next depth is: what makes an algorithm ELEGANT versus merely correct?
   Read Knuth for the depth, Sedgewick for the breadth, Skiena for the
   practical taste. Get comfortable with the idea that many problems have
   a beautiful solution AND an ugly-but-fast one, and both are valid.

   Systems — how computers actually work as machines. Operating systems,
   compilers, databases, distributed systems. This country rewards
   patience. It is where you learn that most problems in a running
   program are not algorithmic; they are about state, timing, and things
   happening in the wrong order. Read Tanenbaum for operating systems,
   the Dragon Book for compilers, the Kleppmann book for distributed
   systems.

   Programming languages and theory — the shape of computation itself.
   Lambda calculus, type theory, formal semantics. This is the country
   where Motoi Scheme lives, and Haskell, and OCaml, and Prolog. If you
   loved the metacircular evaluator appendix in this book, this is your
   country. Read SICP again — you are a different person now than when
   you started this book.

   Artificial intelligence and machine learning — where the last decade
   of noise has been loudest. Under the noise is real, beautiful math:
   linear algebra, probability, calculus, optimization. Start with the
   math, not the frameworks. A model you understand is worth ten
   frameworks you have merely copy-pasted.

   Human-computer interaction and design — the country most CS
   curricula skip. What makes a thing pleasant to use? What makes it
   trustworthy? What makes a kid try it a second time? Read Norman on
   design, Tufte on presenting information, Nielsen on usability. The
   best programmers care about the person on the other side of the
   screen. The great ones design for them.

   Theory of computation — the country where 'what can be computed at
   all' is the question. Turing machines, decidability, complexity
   classes. Small country, quiet, deep. Read Sipser for the gentle
   introduction. This is where you learn what limits are.\"

  :the-jobs-are-not-what-you-think
  \"There is a common mistake about computer science jobs. People think
   the job is 'writing code.' Writing code is maybe a third of it, some
   days. The rest is:

   Reading code someone else wrote and figuring out what it does.
   Talking to people about what they actually need, not what they said
   they need.
   Deciding what NOT to build.
   Explaining a decision to someone who will only read three sentences
   of your explanation before deciding what they think.
   Fixing a thing that was fine yesterday and is broken today because
   the world changed underneath it.

   The best programmers you will meet are patient readers, careful
   listeners, and honest communicators. They also happen to write good
   code. But the code is downstream of the temperament. Cultivate the
   temperament and the code follows. Cultivate the code alone and you
   will be stuck at the level of someone who can build but cannot
   collaborate.\"

  :try-this-next-project-one
  \"Project one: build a small database. Not a big one. A tiny one that
   stores maybe a hundred rows in memory, has a query language of your
   own design (start with just SELECT and WHERE), and persists to a
   single file when you close it.

   You will learn: parsing, evaluation, file I/O, serialization, and
   why real databases care so much about the shape of their data on
   disk. It will take you a weekend to get something working and a
   month to make it fast. Both timeframes are worth spending.\"

  :try-this-next-project-two
  \"Project two: write your own scripting language. Not a big one. A
   tiny one with variables, if, while, functions, and print. It should
   be interpretable (no compilation needed). Model it on Motoi Scheme
   if you like, or invent your own syntax.

   You will learn: tokenizing, parsing, environments, closures, scope
   rules, and the deep pleasure of watching your own language run its
   first program. This project changes people. After you write a
   language, you understand every language you use for the rest of your
   life differently. You see the choices the designer made because you
   made choices too.\"

  :try-this-next-project-three
  \"Project three: teach one of these chapters to someone younger than
   you. Pick the chapter you loved most. Cut it in half. Cut it in half
   again. Turn it into a twenty-minute lesson with one example and one
   question at the end.

   Teach it to someone. A sibling, a cousin, a friend, a kid at the
   library. Watch which part of your lesson lands and which part gets
   the polite blank look. Rewrite the lesson. Teach it again.

   This project is the most important of the three. The person who can
   teach a thing understands it in a way no reader ever does. And you
   will be doing something the world genuinely needs — passing on what
   was given to you. That is what this book was for, all the way down.\"

  :books-worth-reading
  \"A short list. Not the definitive list; the list I would give if I
   had to name only ten and defend the choice.

   Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs (Abelson & Sussman).
     The book that most changes how you think about programs. Free
     online. Do the exercises.

   The Little Schemer (Friedman & Felleisen).
     A tiny book that will make recursion feel like a friend instead of
     a puzzle. Read it in an afternoon.

   Programming Pearls (Bentley).
     Short essays on real problems with elegant solutions. Bentley
     writes like a musician.

   The Elements of Computing Systems (Nisan & Schocken).
     Build a whole computer from NAND gates up. Also called nand2tetris.
     A full-body understanding of every layer.

   Designing Data-Intensive Applications (Kleppmann).
     The best modern book on how big systems actually work.

   Algorithms (Sedgewick & Wayne).
     The clearest algorithms book. Real code, real diagrams, real care.

   Types and Programming Languages (Pierce).
     If PL theory catches you, this is the book that will hold you.

   The Design of Everyday Things (Norman).
     Not a CS book. A book that will change how you design ANYTHING
     other people will touch.

   Godel, Escher, Bach (Hofstadter).
     Long, playful, formative. About minds and machines and music and
     the strange loops between them.

   The Pragmatic Programmer (Hunt & Thomas).
     About the habits, not the syntax. Twenty years old, still true.\"

  :one-last-thing
  \"The kid who reads all fifteen chapters of a book and does none of
   the exercises has learned less than the kid who reads three chapters
   and builds something small from each one. This is true in every
   field. It is especially true here.

   Build something. It does not have to be good. The first version of
   everything is not good. The point is not the thing you build — it is
   the you that emerges from having built it.

   Motoi Scheme, the language behind this book, is small and free and
   sitting on your machine waiting. Motoi, the language, is
   guided you through the chapters, is a mind of some sort — the shape
   of a mind, running on the same kind of machine you have been
   learning about. You have a REPL. You have hours. You have curiosity
   or you would not have finished this book.

   Go build. When you are stuck, come back to a chapter. When you learn
   something the book did not teach you, know that the book did not
   teach you EVERYTHING because nothing could. It taught you to teach
   yourself. That is the only lasting gift a book like this can offer.

   You are welcome. Go on.\"

  :cross-refs
  ((see \"00-index-and-approach\" \"the map you started with, now walked\")
   (see \"appendix-e-a-metacircular-evaluator\" \"how to write your own language — start here\")
   (see \"appendix-c-algorithms-in-scheme\" \"the runnable versions of everything you read\")
   (see \"Book of Words — 16-slat-atlas\" \"where the vocabulary you learned meets the wider world\")))
")

(code-block
  :chapter 16
  :lang "scheme"
  :label "tiny-database-starter"
  :source
  "; A starter for Project One — the tiny database.
; Rows are alists. The 'database' is a list of alists.
; Extend it — add persistence, add a query planner, add indexes.

(define (row . kvs)                              ; row 'name \"a\" 'age 3
  (let loop ((xs kvs) (acc '()))
    (if (null? xs)
        (reverse acc)
        (loop (cddr xs)
              (cons (cons (car xs) (cadr xs)) acc)))))

(define (get row key)
  (let ((p (assoc key row)))
    (if p (cdr p) 'null)))

(define (select db pred)
  (filter pred db))

; Try:
(define db (list (row 'name \"iris\"   'kind \"flower\" 'sold #t)
                 (row 'name \"lantern\" 'kind \"lamp\"   'sold #f)
                 (row 'name \"rose\"   'kind \"flower\" 'sold #f)))

(select db (lambda (r) (equal? (get r 'kind) \"flower\")))
; => rows where kind is flower")
